cs.DB, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.DC, cs.SE 

The paper focuses on applying deep reinforcement learning to data management tasks, specifically in database indexing and resource management in stream processing. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.DB (database) sub-category. Additionally, the paper introduces a TensorFlow library for applied deep reinforcement learning, which falls under the cs.LG (machine learning) sub-category. The use of deep reinforcement learning also suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.AI (artificial intelligence) sub-category. The paper also discusses algorithmic instability and lack of standard tools, which are common issues in distributed computing, suggesting that the paper may belong to the cs.DC (distributed, parallel, and cluster computing) sub-category. Finally, the paper introduces an end-to-end software stack, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.SE (software engineering) sub-category.
